 Your thesis for your master's, I found it online, Ray, but there's one copy of it at

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:12.520
 the library in the University of, where is it, Seattle University?

00:17:12.520 --> 00:17:13.520
 Oregon.

00:17:13.520 --> 00:17:15.720
 Oregon, thank you.

00:17:15.720 --> 00:17:21.000
 Yeah, and I don't think they would allow me to take it out from here.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:27.200
 It was called "William Blake and the Mysticisms of Sense and Nonsense," and I bet it's interesting

00:17:27.200 --> 00:17:29.440
 reading.

00:17:29.440 --> 00:17:46.520
 I concentrated on his philosophy, epistemology and ontology and ethics, and that idea that

00:17:46.520 --> 00:17:57.160
 he was important in all of those areas guided my thinking in science, since it went along

00:17:57.160 --> 00:18:08.880
 with what I had been learning on my own, and that he was putting things together, creating

00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:20.080
 an image of human nature that was very different from anything that dominated our cultural

00:18:20.080 --> 00:18:24.120
 institutions.

00:18:24.120 --> 00:18:27.160
 You were introduced to him in school, you said?

00:18:27.160 --> 00:18:36.400
 Yeah, in a world literature course when I was a sophomore, I think I started and first

00:18:36.400 --> 00:18:43.080
 read some of his forms and saw that his language, even though they had the introduction to that

00:18:43.080 --> 00:18:53.080
 section, described him as a Christian mystic and had his songs of innocence.

00:18:53.080 --> 00:19:03.160
 I could see that there was irony and complexity in his language that was unique in my experience.

00:19:03.160 --> 00:19:14.360
 So I considered him one of the two or three brightest professors at the college, Arthur

00:19:14.360 --> 00:19:27.760
 Kreissman, who let me sign up for a course just in Blake for my third year of college.

00:19:27.760 --> 00:19:36.600
 So I spent that quarter reading people who had commented on Blake, Arthur Prye and Jacob

00:19:36.600 --> 00:19:46.200
 Bernowski, who happened to be a biologist, commenting on the historical setting as well

00:19:46.200 --> 00:19:49.960
 as Blake's own writing.

00:19:49.960 --> 00:19:59.640
 That pretty much formed my philosophical orientation to read and figure out how Blake fit in with

00:19:59.640 --> 00:20:13.840
 the mainline philosophers, Kant, Hegel, Marx, Locke and Hume.

00:20:13.840 --> 00:20:23.520
 Blake had commented on several of his contemporary philosophers and pretty much ridiculed them

00:20:23.520 --> 00:20:28.560
 as he did some of the scientists.

00:20:28.560 --> 00:20:36.160
 As he worked for publishers as an engraver, he was able to be acquainted with the authors

00:20:36.160 --> 00:20:40.360
 that were being published and engraved.

00:20:40.360 --> 00:20:49.560
 So he and Henry Fuseli, the painter, illustrated Erasmus Darwin's books.

00:20:49.560 --> 00:20:58.840
 Erasmus Darwin along with Lamarck really was the main initiator of evolutionary thinking

00:20:58.840 --> 00:21:01.480
 in biology.

00:21:01.480 --> 00:21:14.080
 His grandson, Charles, sort of degraded the concept and turned it into a kind of imperialism

00:21:14.080 --> 00:21:20.400
 along the lines of Malthus.

00:21:20.400 --> 00:21:29.960
 Stress, capitalism and imperialism were shaping a lot of Darwin's ideas.

00:21:29.960 --> 00:21:39.760
 In a later edition, Darwin said, "Well, no, I'm not exclusively saying that competition

00:21:39.760 --> 00:21:50.080
 between species or between individuals is quite natural selection isn't the only thing."

00:21:50.080 --> 00:21:55.480
 He said, "There are other forms of inheritance."

00:21:55.480 --> 00:22:07.400
 So in a weak, second-handed way, he recognized that his grandfather and Lamarck did have

00:22:07.400 --> 00:22:12.840
 some importance.

00:22:12.840 --> 00:22:24.680
 Samuel Butler, in a couple of books, put down Charles Darwin as a phony for misrepresenting

00:22:24.680 --> 00:22:29.480
 who really thought of the idea of evolution of species.

00:22:29.480 --> 00:22:40.960
 Wait a minute, Charles Butler said that he thought of the evolution of species?

00:22:40.960 --> 00:22:44.520
 I didn't follow what you said about Charles Butler, I'm sorry.

00:22:44.520 --> 00:22:54.760
 Samuel Butler wrote, for example, Unconscious Memory, that analyzed the thinking of Erasmus

00:22:54.760 --> 00:23:09.080
 Darwin and Lamarck and showed that memory and inheritance are very similar biological

00:23:09.080 --> 00:23:12.320
 processes.

00:23:12.320 --> 00:23:24.840
 If you look at it in terms of present biology, it would reduce to the idea that genes are

00:23:24.840 --> 00:23:34.640
 always under the influence of chemical modification other than the DNA bases.

00:23:34.640 --> 00:23:40.920
 They're being methylated, for example, and the way they're expressed is modified by several

00:23:40.920 --> 00:23:45.320
 different kinds of chemical reactions.

00:23:45.320 --> 00:23:55.640
 So it's a chemical and physical process that blends between memory and inheritance.

00:23:55.640 --> 00:24:07.280
 And Darwin had acknowledged in the idea of Jammuels something from the whole physiology

00:24:07.280 --> 00:24:09.640
 affecting the inheritance.

00:24:09.640 --> 00:24:20.880
 And Samuel Butler pointed out that Erasmus Darwin and Lamarck had been much more coherent

00:24:20.880 --> 00:24:25.320
 in their description of the process.

00:24:25.320 --> 00:24:32.640
 And it turns out that now we talk about it as epigenetic modification of the DNA and

00:24:32.640 --> 00:24:33.640
 its expression.

00:24:33.640 --> 00:24:46.320
 But for 150 years, the Lamarckian view sort of disappeared from the main currents.

00:24:46.320 --> 00:24:51.720
 And I know we've talked about this before, but why did everybody come down on Lamarck

00:24:51.720 --> 00:24:52.720
 so much?

00:24:52.720 --> 00:24:56.240
 Was it just to justify the social power structure that was in place?

00:24:56.240 --> 00:25:08.800
 Yeah, the man who succeeded him at the French institution denounced him and said that basically

00:25:08.800 --> 00:25:17.200
 he was an anti-Christian with his ideas contradicting the Bible.

00:25:17.200 --> 00:25:30.640
 So there was a lot of Christian theological attack during the 19th century.

00:25:30.640 --> 00:25:41.680
 The current issue tries to put evolution on the side of progress and science and put religion

00:25:41.680 --> 00:25:45.320
 against all of that, which they were in the case of Lamarck.

00:25:45.320 --> 00:25:57.520
 But with Darwin, Darwin became the imperialist philosopher.

00:25:57.520 --> 00:26:03.280
 The strong winning is the direction of progress.

00:26:03.280 --> 00:26:14.360
 So at the time I started graduate school, Conrad

00:26:14.360 --> 00:26:19.560
 Lorentz was about to get the Nobel Prize.

00:26:19.560 --> 00:26:25.440
 There was a whole current in science justifying militarism.

00:26:25.440 --> 00:26:37.600
 And Conrad Lorentz was the ideologist of the Racial Hygiene Institute justifying genocide

00:26:37.600 --> 00:26:39.040
 in Germany.

00:26:39.040 --> 00:26:48.400
 And that was really mainline genetic thinking in America and Germany in the 20s, 30s, and

00:26:48.400 --> 00:26:49.400
 40s.

00:26:49.400 --> 00:26:57.840
 And the defeat of the Nazis made it embarrassing for the Americans to keep using those terms

00:26:57.840 --> 00:27:00.440
 of genocide and so on.

00:27:00.440 --> 00:27:13.560
 By the 60s, Lorentz was being rehabilitated and they were talking about his Nazi beginnings.

00:27:13.560 --> 00:27:28.120
 And my professors were all basically committed to the same genetic determinism.

00:27:28.120 --> 00:27:39.360
 You can see that tendency in Darwin, the way he considered that even botanical species

00:27:39.360 --> 00:27:47.480
 from England were going to displace native species in New Zealand, for example, the way

00:27:47.480 --> 00:27:52.080
 white people were displacing the brown people.

00:27:52.080 --> 00:27:58.040
 Just a real imperialist racist.

00:27:58.040 --> 00:28:06.560
 During the 19th century, a lot of the Christians were going on to Darwin's side along with

00:28:06.560 --> 00:28:08.160
 imperialism.

00:28:08.160 --> 00:28:20.360
 But the Protestant traditions, the same ones that supported the American Revolution, the

00:28:20.360 --> 00:28:29.120
 Great Awakening, had a lot of democratic impulses, equality, anti-slavery.

00:28:29.120 --> 00:28:40.560
 And in the 19th century, feminism and social equality and so on were part of the Protestant

00:28:40.560 --> 00:28:42.840
 or Christian revival.

00:28:42.840 --> 00:28:54.920
 And William Jennings' brand against Clarence Darrow was sort of caricatured the backwardness

00:28:54.920 --> 00:29:00.920
 of people who opposed Darwinism.

00:29:00.920 --> 00:29:16.440
 But the trial, the monkey trial, occurred at the height of the eugenics domination of

00:29:16.440 --> 00:29:18.720
 biological thinking.

00:29:18.720 --> 00:29:33.600
 And William Jennings' brand represented the public common persons and anti-racial thinking

00:29:33.600 --> 00:29:44.640
 with Clarence Darrow siding with the imperialists and racists and Brian siding with the common

00:29:44.640 --> 00:29:49.320
 person against racism and genocide.

00:29:49.320 --> 00:29:55.920
 And he didn't put it in the proper political language.

00:29:55.920 --> 00:30:05.080
 And so he's been ridiculed ever since as an ignorant person opposing progress.

00:30:05.080 --> 00:30:12.600
 But when you look at it in the context of who the geneticists really were, the people

00:30:12.600 --> 00:30:21.840
 who set up Hitler's genocide, and you see that Brian and the Christians were really

00:30:21.840 --> 00:30:25.040
 on the right side.

00:30:25.040 --> 00:30:28.480
 On the side for human rights, basically.

00:30:28.480 --> 00:30:30.440
 Yeah, basically.

00:30:30.440 --> 00:30:41.800
 And Blake was at the center of all of those movements that influenced American history

00:30:41.800 --> 00:30:54.920
 and scientific thinking, philosophical thinking in that sort of underground, unofficial atmosphere.

00:30:54.920 --> 00:31:04.560
 Well, he certainly had an incredibly productive lifespan, and both in art.

00:31:04.560 --> 00:31:10.440
 I don't know if everybody out there has seen his paintings and etchings and drawings, but

00:31:10.440 --> 00:31:14.000
 they're certainly astounding to look at.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:21.800
 And in addition to the artwork, he writes an immense amount of poetry that goes with

00:31:21.800 --> 00:31:23.960
 it and some of its prose too, I suppose.

00:31:23.960 --> 00:31:33.040
 But he's an amazingly accomplished person for somebody who never, from our point of

00:31:33.040 --> 00:31:36.120
 view these days, from somebody who never went to school.

00:31:36.120 --> 00:31:40.960
 Maybe you could comment a little bit on his education, such as it was.

00:31:40.960 --> 00:31:47.840
 Yeah, he went to a drawing school, I think, when he was 10, and then was apprenticed to

00:31:47.840 --> 00:31:51.120
 an engraver when he was 15.

00:31:51.120 --> 00:31:58.800
 And he started associating with the educated people through the engraver when he was an

00:31:58.800 --> 00:32:09.360
 apprentice and was writing poetry in his late teens and early 20s.

00:32:09.360 --> 00:32:23.120
 But as simply a craftsman, he was not really at the center of their movement, which was

00:32:23.120 --> 00:32:28.760
 educated writers who were getting published and having people illustrate their books.

00:32:28.760 --> 00:32:37.400
 So he knew these people and became friends with some of them, like William Godwin and

00:32:37.400 --> 00:32:47.840
 Mary Wollstonecraft, and Joseph Priestley, the oxygen guy, who was also the founder of

00:32:47.840 --> 00:32:54.640
 Unitarianism, or one of the founders.

00:32:54.640 --> 00:33:05.320
 These people were the radicals and progressives who were actually in danger of being imprisoned

00:33:05.320 --> 00:33:09.200
 or killed by the government for their opinions.

00:33:09.200 --> 00:33:20.280
 Some of Blake's acquaintances were tried for treason in 1795.

00:33:20.280 --> 00:33:32.600
 The atmosphere among the people was such that all three of the first ones tried were acquitted

00:33:32.600 --> 00:33:40.400
 by the juries, and the government had 30 other people indicted.

00:33:40.400 --> 00:33:48.760
 They dropped the cases against them because it was getting so embarrassing because the

00:33:48.760 --> 00:33:56.680
 transcripts of the trials were being published, and it was hurting the government to lose

00:33:56.680 --> 00:34:04.120
 the cases and get all of this publicity for the anti-government view.

00:34:04.120 --> 00:34:09.760
 They had a list of 500 that they intended to prosecute if they had been winning with

00:34:09.760 --> 00:34:10.760
 the juries.

00:34:10.760 --> 00:34:16.680
 And these people were all accused of treason against the king?

00:34:16.680 --> 00:34:30.240
 Yeah, high treason for belonging to the corresponding society, which stayed in touch with the revolutionaries

00:34:30.240 --> 00:34:33.720
 in America and France.

00:34:33.720 --> 00:34:45.320
 And it was treason to express opposition to a monarchy.

00:34:45.320 --> 00:34:53.400
 The law actually said it had to lead to armed rebellion, but the prosecutors were bending

00:34:53.400 --> 00:34:59.080
 the interpretation and saying that having a bad attitude was treasonous.

00:34:59.080 --> 00:35:06.480
 Yeah, a violent, rebellious attitude.

00:35:06.480 --> 00:35:13.800
 So it sounds like Blake was doing a lot of reading, and he was right in the thick of

00:35:13.800 --> 00:35:18.480
 whatever cultural movements were happening at that point.

00:35:18.480 --> 00:35:20.600
 Did he read science also?

00:35:20.600 --> 00:35:33.760
 Yeah, his parents were for a time attending the Swedenborgian church, and Swedenborg was

00:35:33.760 --> 00:35:44.880
 a real scientist who did some very 100-year premature nerve research.

00:35:44.880 --> 00:35:56.240
 So Blake knew a lot about nervous anatomy, biology in general, and knew all of the scientists

00:35:56.240 --> 00:36:10.080
 in London really, at least to the extent of reading things that the publishers had.

00:36:10.080 --> 00:36:20.840
 Because so many of them were radicals in opposing monarchy, he was friendly with them politically,

00:36:20.840 --> 00:36:31.880
 but he didn't accept their rationalistic, stylish way of thinking about reality.

00:36:31.880 --> 00:36:43.640
 Priestley had some ideas that Blake found scientifically justifiable, such as energy.

00:36:43.640 --> 00:36:53.520
 He and Priestley believed that matter was made up of energy, and Blake saw energy as

00:36:53.520 --> 00:36:57.680
 being the essence of human life.

00:36:57.680 --> 00:37:11.840
 He once referred to being so inspired that sparks were coming out of his fingers.

00:37:11.840 --> 00:37:26.000
 The main scientific mood of those deists and rationalists was that reason was where attention

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:38.040
 should be put rather than on experience, and that matter was some sort of an inert something,

00:37:38.040 --> 00:37:43.840
 like having intrinsic energy.

00:37:43.840 --> 00:37:54.640
 It was an idea about matter that a lot of people still have, that consciousness can't

00:37:54.640 --> 00:38:02.120
 possibly come out of matter because matter is something that has to be pushed around

00:38:02.120 --> 00:38:12.920
 by extrinsic forces like billiard balls.

00:38:12.920 --> 00:38:24.200
 So Blake was doing better thinking about the philosophy of science even than Joseph Priestley,

00:38:24.200 --> 00:38:32.800
 especially the worst mechanists.

00:38:32.800 --> 00:38:49.200
 He not only was putting energy into matter, but he wanted to see experience as a part

00:38:49.200 --> 00:38:58.040
 of the nature of matter, that everything was following the same principles, whether it

00:38:58.040 --> 00:39:09.160
 was a piece of sand or a bug or a person.

00:39:09.160 --> 00:39:20.440
 The energy and interaction were the essential properties of matter and of life.

00:39:20.440 --> 00:39:31.320
 So it's a building aspect of matter that it actually gains complexity?

00:39:31.320 --> 00:39:35.240
 It gains what?

00:39:35.240 --> 00:39:36.240
 Complexity?

00:39:36.240 --> 00:39:42.640
 Oh yeah.

00:39:42.640 --> 00:39:56.800
 He sometimes called the principle of life or of knowing the poetic genius, and this

00:39:56.800 --> 00:40:06.200
 he saw as being a universal thing, that a plant or an animal, its form was expressing

00:40:06.200 --> 00:40:08.920
 its poetic genius.

00:40:08.920 --> 00:40:19.480
 So it was kind of a lively version of Spinoza's pantheism.

00:40:19.480 --> 00:40:33.280
 He didn't see any separation between matter, energy, and consciousness, and believed that

00:40:33.280 --> 00:40:43.200
 experience was, he even said experiment was the true form of knowing.

00:40:43.200 --> 00:40:58.600
 The experiencing person couldn't derive anything new from previously learned knowledge, and

00:40:58.600 --> 00:41:08.960
 this sort of offended the university educated people who believed that they had learned

00:41:08.960 --> 00:41:12.440
 something important at the university.

00:41:12.440 --> 00:41:21.200
 And Blake was saying that every moment we're experiencing something new that is changing

00:41:21.200 --> 00:41:24.600
 what we did know.

00:41:24.600 --> 00:41:35.520
 And so the canonical knowledge that you get at the university is always necessarily in

00:41:35.520 --> 00:41:37.280
 doubt.

00:41:37.280 --> 00:41:46.160
 But Blake said you can't doubt from what you experience, you can only, you can doubt,

00:41:46.160 --> 00:41:50.960
 have to doubt everything that people tell you is true.

00:41:50.960 --> 00:41:59.280
 But experience can't be doubted because that's what it is.

00:41:59.280 --> 00:42:03.200
 So we have a question, email question just came in concerning Blake.

00:42:03.200 --> 00:42:09.680
 It's from Jose Gonzalez, and it says, in your William Blake article you briefly talk about

00:42:09.680 --> 00:42:13.720
 the difference between the craftsman and the academic.

00:42:13.720 --> 00:42:17.920
 Can you go into further detail describing the difference between them and the knowledge

00:42:17.920 --> 00:42:20.560
 acquired by each one?

00:42:20.560 --> 00:42:36.120
 Yeah, the craftsman, I studied etching and dry-plained printmaking for a while to experience

00:42:36.120 --> 00:42:39.880
 something of what he was doing.

00:42:39.880 --> 00:42:52.160
 And I saw that working on a copper plate with a needle and drawing with this very fine point

00:42:52.160 --> 00:43:02.920
 and making fine lines to build up shapes, after I'd been doing it for a few hours, the

00:43:02.920 --> 00:43:17.280
 sparkly colors of the refraction lines in the copper created a sort of iridescent quality.

00:43:17.280 --> 00:43:24.640
 And for hours after I'd been working on a plate, I would see that quality in everything

00:43:24.640 --> 00:43:27.760
 I looked at.

00:43:27.760 --> 00:43:38.480
 And Blake described that sort of experience, that you enliven your senses by working on

00:43:38.480 --> 00:43:46.120
 something and that extends to every new experience you have.

00:43:46.120 --> 00:43:53.280
 You're shaping it yourself while the new stuff is coming in.

00:43:53.280 --> 00:44:01.080
 And the person who works only on the level of knowledge, what the book and the professor

00:44:01.080 --> 00:44:11.440
 say, that builds up a similar set of reflexes in that person.

00:44:11.440 --> 00:44:17.360
 So they go out seeing the world in terms of what the book and the professor have said.

00:44:17.360 --> 00:44:27.640
 So they see the world as talking concepts to them, rather than the craftsman feels the

00:44:27.640 --> 00:44:42.320
 world in a sensory newness corresponding to how he's been using his body and mind in working.

00:44:42.320 --> 00:44:52.440
 So he feels the world working back at him with those same properties that he has been

00:44:52.440 --> 00:44:53.440
 enlivening.

00:44:53.440 --> 00:44:56.440
 Yeah, that's interesting.

00:44:56.440 --> 00:45:03.120
 There's another question you brought up, Blake's perception of the world when he was working.

00:45:03.120 --> 00:45:10.560
 And Todd Mudd asks via email, "The first biography of William Blake by Alexander Gilchrist makes

00:45:10.560 --> 00:45:15.520
 frequent mention of Blake's hallucinations and visions and emphasizes the importance

00:45:15.520 --> 00:45:18.760
 Blake and his wife placed on those visions.

00:45:18.760 --> 00:45:23.080
 According to the biography, when Blake wanted to draw a famous historical person, he would

00:45:23.080 --> 00:45:27.080
 act as if its ghost was sitting literally in front of him.

00:45:27.080 --> 00:45:30.900
 Sometimes the ghost image wouldn't come and Blake would have to wait until its visitation

00:45:30.900 --> 00:45:33.600
 later in order to make the drawing.

00:45:33.600 --> 00:45:38.080
 I think it's more well known that Blake saw angels as a child and was reprimanded for

00:45:38.080 --> 00:45:40.080
 this revelation.

00:45:40.080 --> 00:45:45.840
 What do you make of Blake's visions?" is the question.

00:45:45.840 --> 00:45:58.040
 I think it's that way of thinking which kids normally have and it gets trained out of them.

00:45:58.040 --> 00:46:10.200
 You can't use metaphors and imagery too much if the world around you doesn't like novel

00:46:10.200 --> 00:46:11.200
 perceptions.

00:46:11.200 --> 00:46:18.120
 You mean you have to stick to the conventional images or else you'll be ostracized?

00:46:18.120 --> 00:46:31.800
 Yeah, and the body has this capacity to concretize to different extents its thoughts, but most

00:46:31.800 --> 00:46:42.600
 people get stuck in the concretizing the thoughts as words and they start to think of the word

00:46:42.600 --> 00:46:51.560
 as somehow the identity of the concept and the concept as the identity of what's in the

00:46:51.560 --> 00:46:54.600
 world.

00:46:54.600 --> 00:47:07.240
 If you see that your body can bring up these concrete images as you think, that gives you

00:47:07.240 --> 00:47:17.400
 a much more fluid attitude towards everything you learn.

00:47:17.400 --> 00:47:25.920
 You see right in front of you your thought process and the well-trained, well-educated

00:47:25.920 --> 00:47:42.400
 person sees words as their consciousness and the words tend to carry with them all of the

00:47:42.400 --> 00:47:46.960
 intentions of the educational system.

00:47:46.960 --> 00:47:57.840
 So that's the cage that people built in their minds that trap their whole being in this

00:47:57.840 --> 00:47:59.840
 world of words and concepts.

00:47:59.840 --> 00:48:06.520
 I see, so we just sort of get lost in our abstractions.

00:48:06.520 --> 00:48:10.920
 In someone else's abstractions, actually.

00:48:10.920 --> 00:48:19.600
 And extending those abstractions and Blake repeatedly emphasized that you can't get useful

00:48:19.600 --> 00:48:22.640
 knowledge from previously acquired knowledge.

00:48:22.640 --> 00:48:25.120
 I mean, words are so tied to images.

00:48:25.120 --> 00:48:32.480
 It seems like whenever I read something, it brings up an image of some kind and I would

00:48:32.480 --> 00:48:36.320
 think in a way they go hand in hand.

00:48:36.320 --> 00:48:44.040
 Yeah, it depends on really how you read and how your mind works.

00:48:44.040 --> 00:48:49.760
 For a while I was a major in psychology in graduate school.

00:48:49.760 --> 00:49:02.960
 One of my projects was to do a questionnaire and find creative people versus good students

00:49:02.960 --> 00:49:05.080
 in various departments.

00:49:05.080 --> 00:49:16.760
 And the people who were somewhat non-conformist and creative, productive, always turned out

00:49:16.760 --> 00:49:26.240
 to have a different way of thinking, even of dreaming.

00:49:26.240 --> 00:49:36.280
 The most conventional good student type tended to even have boring language-centered dreams

00:49:36.280 --> 00:49:48.800
 versus the richer, more complex-colored and interesting kind of dreaming and thinking.

00:49:48.800 --> 00:49:50.680
 So they actually think in symbols.

00:49:50.680 --> 00:49:51.680
 Yeah.

00:49:51.680 --> 00:49:58.760
 Oh, go on if you were going to say something.

00:49:58.760 --> 00:50:00.520
 Were you going to go on about that?

00:50:00.520 --> 00:50:01.520
 No.

00:50:01.520 --> 00:50:02.520
 Okay.

00:50:02.520 --> 00:50:06.920
 Well, I was wondering about, I mean, I think the idea of the image is so interesting.

00:50:06.920 --> 00:50:12.320
 You mentioned in another show about synectics, I think it was called.

00:50:12.320 --> 00:50:13.320
 Synectics.

00:50:13.320 --> 00:50:15.320
 Synectic, thank you.

00:50:15.320 --> 00:50:18.520
 I spelled it wrong.

00:50:18.520 --> 00:50:20.600
 Well, why don't you explain what that was?

00:50:20.600 --> 00:50:25.040
 And they used images or metaphors for solving problems, is that right?

00:50:25.040 --> 00:50:27.720
 Which reminds me of Blake somehow.

00:50:27.720 --> 00:50:36.400
 Yeah, the original Synectics book by W. J. J. Gordon was one I was talking about.

00:50:36.400 --> 00:50:41.680
 It has since evolved into some kind of other business.

00:50:41.680 --> 00:50:48.040
 But he, in the 50s, developed this group.

00:50:48.040 --> 00:50:54.840
 First they were trying to understand the creative process in art.

00:50:54.840 --> 00:51:05.520
 And they realized that there was no objective way to prove what was better in the art.

00:51:05.520 --> 00:51:13.600
 So they went to engineering and things that could have a concrete outcome that they could

00:51:13.600 --> 00:51:14.960
 sell.

00:51:14.960 --> 00:51:21.040
 And eventually it turned into working, just solving corporation problems.

00:51:21.040 --> 00:51:33.200
 But while they were developing the technique to understand how the brain is creative, they

00:51:33.200 --> 00:51:40.280
 developed these different ways of using imagery and body feeling, putting yourself into the

00:51:40.280 --> 00:51:49.520
 problem, imagining the problem in different perspectives.

00:51:49.520 --> 00:51:53.160
 And that helped people think out of the box, as they say.

00:51:53.160 --> 00:51:54.160
 Yeah.

00:51:54.160 --> 00:51:55.160
 Yeah.

00:51:55.160 --> 00:52:00.000
 And I was also curious, in the subject of visions and Blake, I guess he saw them his

00:52:00.000 --> 00:52:01.000
 whole life.

00:52:01.000 --> 00:52:07.000
 And he definitely made good use of them in his artwork.

00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:16.760
 And how do you, or do you relate that at all to Carl Jung and his basically, his, I don't

00:52:16.760 --> 00:52:22.720
 know if you call it popularizing, but his, he seemed to bring to the public's attention

00:52:22.720 --> 00:52:25.920
 the fact that those images are available to all of us.

00:52:25.920 --> 00:52:33.520
 And they're in fact, according to his theory, indicative of a basically a whole other level

00:52:33.520 --> 00:52:39.400
 of mental activity, which you call the unconscious, that's going on within all of us all the time

00:52:39.400 --> 00:52:42.520
 and driving much of what we do, even though we're not aware of it.

00:52:42.520 --> 00:52:45.960
 And do you relate that to Blake at all?

00:52:45.960 --> 00:52:47.400
 Oh, sure.

00:52:47.400 --> 00:52:59.560
 I just think Jung didn't, he was sort of on the fringes of Freudian thinking, but still

00:52:59.560 --> 00:53:08.280
 I think he was tied to the same culture that affected Freud.

00:53:08.280 --> 00:53:15.520
 And Wilhelm Wright, even though he didn't talk about images, I think was closer to Blake

00:53:15.520 --> 00:53:22.320
 in attitude than any of the people in that psychoanalytic culture.

00:53:22.320 --> 00:53:23.320
 I see.

00:53:23.320 --> 00:53:29.880
 So how would you rate this, relate the psychoanalytic culture to Blake?

00:53:29.880 --> 00:53:33.360
 It sounds like you're thinking they're off base somewhat.

00:53:33.360 --> 00:53:45.800
 Well, Freud with his superego and id, the id had to be repressed to form a rational

00:53:45.800 --> 00:53:47.520
 ego.

00:53:47.520 --> 00:54:03.360
 And Wilhelm Wright pointed out that the superego included the Nazis and other absolutely undesirable

00:54:03.360 --> 00:54:13.880
 oppressors and that the id really had most of what was good in humanity and shouldn't

00:54:13.880 --> 00:54:16.080
 be repressed.

00:54:16.080 --> 00:54:26.680
 And so Wright had sex political organizations and got in all kinds of trouble in Europe

00:54:26.680 --> 00:54:35.600
 by saying that people should be sexually free and combining that with socialistic political

00:54:35.600 --> 00:54:37.440
 ideas.

00:54:37.440 --> 00:54:47.000
 And the sexual thing came out of Freudianism, but Freud pleased the authorities by saying

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:54.080
 you must repress it and accept authority.

00:54:54.080 --> 00:55:07.560
 And Blake, according to some of his biographers, who was sexually a very advanced thinker,

00:55:07.560 --> 00:55:17.280
 didn't believe that women should be the property of their husbands and such.

00:55:17.280 --> 00:55:19.560
 And where would you fit Jung into all that?

00:55:19.560 --> 00:55:25.240
 Because he disagreed pretty violently with Freud about a lot of things.

00:55:25.240 --> 00:55:38.440
 Yeah, I think his emphasis on imagery is very good, but he tried to stereotype it into sort

00:55:38.440 --> 00:55:42.640
 of perpetual personality types.

00:55:42.640 --> 00:55:53.560
 And Blake would have said that we have we and worms and everybody has certain properties,

00:55:53.560 --> 00:55:57.720
 but we're always going someplace new.

00:55:57.720 --> 00:56:07.680
 That you can't say that a person is bound to any one of these personality types.

00:56:07.680 --> 00:56:08.960
 I see.

00:56:08.960 --> 00:56:16.880
 So he didn't want to stereotype any living thing, it sounds like.

00:56:16.880 --> 00:56:18.040
 Yeah.

00:56:18.040 --> 00:56:29.040
 Each thing is different in its unique species and individual personality.

00:56:29.040 --> 00:56:41.480
 But within that species and form, every individual is always becoming something new.

00:56:41.480 --> 00:56:53.880
 And I think a lot of his epistemology, that basing experience, putting experience as the

00:56:53.880 --> 00:57:03.800
 basis of all knowledge, I think that grew directly out of his thinking about evolution

00:57:03.800 --> 00:57:13.120
 and reading Erasmus Darwin's thinking about evolution.

00:57:13.120 --> 00:57:25.320
 Blake saw that each thing, the lamb and the tiger, each one had its own character or genius.

00:57:25.320 --> 00:57:42.320
 But each one was also an individual experiencing and has to be free to be itself and to, like

00:57:42.320 --> 00:57:55.360
 the human, has to always be exploring, getting new sensory information.

00:57:55.360 --> 00:58:06.640
 And how does the image, the idea of the image in Blake was so amazing with creating these

00:58:06.640 --> 00:58:15.440
 fantastic and yet very specific images and saying basically how he felt the world worked,

00:58:15.440 --> 00:58:27.800
 how does that all relate to his ideas about science?

00:58:27.800 --> 00:58:45.440
 I think Wilhelm Reich, as thinking about science, he said that the people who identify with

00:58:45.440 --> 00:58:57.400
 what Freud called the super-ego, they want to put all life in spiritual things and that

00:58:57.400 --> 00:59:04.280
 makes them see the body as a worthless lump.

00:59:04.280 --> 00:59:18.760
 And matter versus spirit is an absolute contradiction in that Freudian thinking that Wilhelm Reich

00:59:18.760 --> 00:59:30.280
 emphasized over and over that matter itself is the source of experience and knowledge

00:59:30.280 --> 00:59:38.400
 and it's a deformation of personality that makes people think about matter as something

00:59:38.400 --> 00:59:44.480
 else, something outside of consciousness and knowledge.

00:59:44.480 --> 00:59:51.760
 The Kantian idea that the thing in itself is unknowable, where Blake and Reich would

00:59:51.760 --> 01:00:08.000
 say that the genius of matter is what knows.

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:14.720
 It was about resonance and interaction and such.

01:00:14.720 --> 01:00:25.560
 Electricity was a great interest in the whole culture, not just in so-called sciences, but

01:00:25.560 --> 01:00:37.320
 the idea of electrical interactions entered into common thinking so that people were getting

01:00:37.320 --> 01:00:46.040
 so-called medical treatments by getting shocked with mild electrical current.

01:00:46.040 --> 01:00:59.840
 So this idea of energy as part of life, some places Blake said there's no body distinct

01:00:59.840 --> 01:01:09.400
 from the soul, but other places he identified the body with energy.

01:01:09.400 --> 01:01:18.040
 What he was denying was that there is this inert nature behind what we experience as

01:01:18.040 --> 01:01:21.160
 nature.

01:01:21.160 --> 01:01:30.840
 There is no such thing as a thing in itself which is this inert, passive matter.

01:01:30.840 --> 01:01:35.000
 He's saying it's all energy, not inert.

01:01:35.000 --> 01:01:36.000
 Yeah.

